div.h1: GDT Descriptor Binary Layout 8-Byte Microscopic View

g.text: Byte 6 Flags Nibble [7:4] and Limit High [3:0]
Access Byte Errors That ALWAYS Triple Fault
NASM Source Annotated with Field Positions

text.tspan: Bit positions: [7] P | [6:5] DPL | [4] S | [3:1] Type | [0] A
Triple fault if P=0, DPL wrong, or Type bits incorrect
0x9A = 1001 1010 Kernel Code R0 P=1 DPL=00 S=1 Type=1010
0x92 = 1001 0010 Kernel Data R0 P=1 DPL=00 S=1 Type=0010
0xFA = 1111 1010 User Code R3 P=1 DPL=11 S=1 Type=1010
0xF2 = 1111 0010 User Data R3 P=1 DPL=11 S=1 Type=0010
0x00 = 0000 0000 NULL entry All zero loading = GPF
Fix: Always set bit 7 of access byte
CPU reads as System descriptor type
First memory access = GPF triple fault
Fix: Bit 4 S=1 for code and data segs
DANGER: No far jump after CR0.PE=1
Fix: MANDATORY far jump after CR0.PE=1
Fix: Bit 6 of byte 6 must = 1 for 32-bit
Fields are NON-CONTIGUOUS by Intel 286 extension design
Base and Limit are split across non-adjacent bytes
Backward-compat decision from 1985 that persists today

g.text: Green = Safe / Correct for flat model
